News Corp. Shares Surge Most in Two Years in Sydney After Analyst Upgrades

-- B y   K a z u y o   S a w a
-- 
2011-08-12T02:38:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-12/news-corp-shares-surge-most-in-two-years-in-sydney-after-analyst-upgrades.html
News Corp. (NWSA) , owner of Fox TV and the
Wall Street Journal, jumped the most in more than two years in
Sydney trading after analysts upgraded their recommendations on
the stock.  The shares gained as much as 8.6 percent, the biggest
intraday gain since May 2009, and traded 6.7 percent higher at
A$15.74 as of 12:35 p.m. on the Australian Securities Exchange.
News Corp. Class A shares surged 18 percent to $16.19 at 4 p.m.
New York time on the Nasdaq Stock Market.  Gabelli & Co. raised its rating on billionaire  Rupert Murdoch ’s News Corp. to “buy” from “hold,” while Atlantic
Securities boosted the stock to “overweight” from “neutral.”  In a conference call this week, the New York-based company
said it will spend more than $5 billion to buy back shares from
next week. Chief Operating Officer  Chase Carey  said News Corp.’s
acquisition strategy focuses on investments in the “tens or
hundreds of millions, not billions.”  To contact the reporters on this story:
